The polynomial system that corresponds to finding the h, e, f triple:
\(\begin{array}{rcl}x_{1} x_{7} -6&=&0\\x_{2} x_{8} -10&=&0\\x_{3} x_{9} -12&=&0\\x_{3} x_{9} -12&=&0\\x_{3} x_{9} -12&=&0\\x_{4} x_{10} -12&=&0\\x_{5} x_{11} -10&=&0\\x_{6} x_{12} -6&=&0\\\end{array}\)
Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.
More precisely, the chevalley generators participating in f are ordered in the order in which their roots appear, and the coefficients are chosen to be the increasing odd numbers 1, 3, 5, ....
This arbitrary (but well-defined) choice of f guarantees that the computation is linear and fast.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.
More precisely, the chevalley generators participating in f are ordered in the order in which their roots appear, and the coefficients are chosen to be the increasing odd numbers 1, 3, 5, ....
This arbitrary (but well-defined) choice of f guarantees that the computation is linear and fast.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.
More precisely, the chevalley generators participating in f are ordered in the order in which their roots appear, and the coefficients are chosen to be the increasing odd numbers 1, 3, 5, ....
This arbitrary (but well-defined) choice of f guarantees that the computation is linear and fast.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.
More precisely, the chevalley generators participating in f are ordered in the order in which their roots appear, and the coefficients are chosen to be the increasing odd numbers 1, 3, 5, ....
This arbitrary (but well-defined) choice of f guarantees that the computation is linear and fast.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.
More precisely, the chevalley generators participating in f are ordered in the order in which their roots appear, and the coefficients are chosen to be the increasing odd numbers 1, 3, 5, ....
This arbitrary (but well-defined) choice of f guarantees that the computation is linear and fast.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.
More precisely, the chevalley generators participating in f are ordered in the order in which their roots appear, and the coefficients are chosen to be the increasing odd numbers 1, 3, 5, ....
This arbitrary (but well-defined) choice of f guarantees that the computation is linear and fast.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.

More precisely, the chevalley generators participating in f are ordered in the order in which their roots appear, and the coefficients are chosen to be the increasing odd numbers 1, 3, 5, ....
This arbitrary (but well-defined) choice of f guarantees that the computation is linear and fast.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.
More precisely, the chevalley generators participating in f are ordered in the order in which their roots appear, and the coefficients are chosen to be the increasing odd numbers 1, 3, 5, ....
This arbitrary (but well-defined) choice of f guarantees that the computation is linear and fast.
\(\begin{array}{rcl}h&=&3h_{8}+5h_{7}+6h_{6}+6h_{5}+6h_{4}+6h_{3}+5h_{2}+3h_{1}\\e&=&x_{2} g_{24}+x_{4} g_{23}+x_{3} g_{15}+x_{5} g_{14}+x_{1} g_{9}\\f&=&g_{-9}+17g_{-14}+5g_{-15}+10g_{-23}+2g_{-24}\end{array}\)

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.
More precisely, the chevalley generators participating in f are ordered in the order in which their roots appear, and the coefficients are chosen to be the increasing odd numbers 1, 3, 5, ....
This arbitrary (but well-defined) choice of f guarantees that the computation is linear and fast.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.
More precisely, the chevalley generators participating in f are ordered in the order in which their roots appear, and the coefficients are chosen to be the increasing odd numbers 1, 3, 5, ....
This arbitrary (but well-defined) choice of f guarantees that the computation is linear and fast.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.
More precisely, the chevalley generators participating in f are ordered in the order in which their roots appear, and the coefficients are chosen to be the increasing odd numbers 1, 3, 5, ....
This arbitrary (but well-defined) choice of f guarantees that the computation is linear and fast.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.
More precisely, the chevalley generators participating in f are ordered in the order in which their roots appear, and the coefficients are chosen to be the increasing odd numbers 1, 3, 5, ....
This arbitrary (but well-defined) choice of f guarantees that the computation is linear and fast.

Starting h, e, f triple. H is computed according to Dynkin, and the coefficients of f are arbitrarily chosen.
